(Constraint
    "PascalCase at the start of `(…)` is ALWAYS an enum variant. Always. There is no 'sometimes it's a struct head'. Structs have NO type tag in the wire form — they are just positional fields. When the wire shows a PascalCase token, you are looking at an enum variant. When the wire shows `(value1 value2 …)` with no PascalCase token first, you are looking at a struct. The nota/README.md claim that 'records require a PascalCase head' is wrong because it conflates structs with enum variants. NOTA has three kinds of values: structs (positional fields, no tag), enums (variants tagged by their PascalCase name), and primitives (strings, ints, bools, etc., which fill struct fields). Rule 1 of skills/nota-design.md ('drop the wrapper if every record is the same kind') is the SAME rule: if every record is the same kind, there is no enum — it's just a struct, no tag."
    "The only reason there's a, what you're calling a type name is a variant. Always, always, always, always, always. … We don't need to say that it's a skill every time because there's no variant. There's not like another thing there. It's only a skill. So it's a struct. … The only, what you're calling a type is a variant, is an enum. It's the variant of an enum. There's only structs and enums and strings. … when you see a variant, when you see a pascal case thing at the beginning, that's a variant. That means you're talking about an enum. Automatic."
    "Seventh NOTA correction. The mental model I was missing: PascalCase tag = enum variant, always. No tag = struct. That's the binary. Rule 1 of nota-design.md becomes 'drop the variant tag if there's only one variant — because then it's a struct, not an enum.' The README needs the same correction in primary-hj63."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19 20:45)

(Decision
    "NOTA's PascalCase-token mental model is three cases. `(VariantName fields…)` = data-carrying enum variant (everything after the variant name is its data). `(fields…)` without a leading PascalCase = struct. Bare `VariantName` with no preceding `(` = non-data-carrying unit variant. That covers every PascalCase usage in NOTA. Agents repeatedly miss this because it has never been documented this cleanly."
    "when you have something like what we have in the current nota files for intent, so first opens a parentheses, right? Then you have a Pascal case identifier. So because you've opened a parentheses and there's a Pascal case, that means you have a data-carrying variant. And everything after the first Pascal case identifier, which is the variant name, is the data of the variant. … If there's a parenthesis and it doesn't start with a variant name, then it's a struct. If there's a parenthesis and it starts with a variant name, then it's a data-carrying variant. If there's no parenthesis before, there's no opening parenthesis before the variant name, then it's a non-data-carrying variant."
    "The clean three-case rule. Replaces my prior invented terminology and partial framings. Lands in skills/nota-design.md and feeds bead primary-hj63 for the README rewrite."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19 21:00)

